Dorsal macrochaetotaxy (
). Dorsal macrochaetotaxy provides the main diagnostic characters to separate species and genera across Entomobryoidea when there is no color pattern, as it is the case for troglobiotic species. Macrochaetotaxic pattern of H . ( V .) absoloni and H . ( V .) gamae sp. nov .
is identical on most tergites but exhibits important differences on head and Abd. IV (
). Differences on head concern the number of mac in anterior ( 3 + 3 with one unpaired vs 2 + 2 without unpaired), median ( 2 + 2 vs 1 + 1 ), antennal ( 8 vs 6 ) and sutural ( 6 + 6 vs 6–7 + 6–7 ) groups on head. The 1 + 1 chaetae between antennae are absent in H . ( V .) gamae sp. nov. Differences on body concern the chaetotaxy of Abd. IV (
): number of mac in medial ( 3 vs. 4 ), anterolateral ( 4 vs 3 ) and posterolateral ( 4 vs 2 ) groups in H . ( V .) absoloni versus H . ( V .) gamae sp. nov. Additionally, specimens of H . ( V .) gamae sp. nov. have 1 or 2 mac in posteromedial group.

